				<text>35.4.3.3 Jobs</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<h4 class="HELM_exercise"> Exercise </h4>
<p> A company advertises a job in three newspapers, \(P_A\), \(P_B\) and \(P_C\). It
is known that these papers attract undergraduate readerships in the
proportions \(2:3:1\). The probabilities that an undergraduate replies
to the job advertisement after they see it in these papers&nbsp;are \(\displaystyle{@pra@}\), \(\displaystyle{@prb@}\) and \(\displaystyle{@prc@}\) respectively. Assume that the undergraduate sees only one job advertisement. Let\[\begin{aligned}A &amp;= \{\text{Person is a reader of paper }P_A\},\\ B &amp;= \{\text{Person is a reader of paper }P_B\},\\ C &amp;= \{\text{Person is a reader of paper }P_C\},\\ R &amp;= \{\text{Reader applies for the job}\}.\end{aligned}\]
</p>
<ol class="HELM_parts">
<li> If the company receives only one reply to it advertisements, calculate the probability that the applicant has seen the job advertised in \(P_A\), \(P_B\) or \(P_C\). Specifically, calculate that probabilities \(\mathbb{P}(A|R)\), \(\mathbb{P}(B|R)\), \(\mathbb{P}(C|R)\).</li>
<li> If the company receives two replies, what is the probability that both
applicants saw the job advertised in paper \(P_A\)? I.e. let \(D = \{\text{Both applicants read }P_A\}\) and calculate \(\mathbb{P}(D)\). Assume the readerships and replies are independent. </li>
</ol>
<p> Give all probabilities as fractions, not decimals: </p>
<ol class="HELM_parts">
<li> \(\mathbb{P}(A|R)=\quad\)[[input:ans1]][[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]], \(\quad\mathbb{P}(B|R)=\quad\)[[input:ans2]][[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]], \(\quad\mathbb{P}(C|R)=\quad\)[[input:ans3]][[validation:ans3]][[feedback:prt3]] </li>
<li> \(\mathbb{P}(D)=\quad\)[[input:ans4]][[validation:ans4]][[feedback:prt4]] </li>
</ol>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<h4 class="HELM_solution"> Solution </h4>
<p> We have the probabilities\[\begin{aligned}\mathbb{P}(A) &amp;= {@pa@};\quad\mathbb{P}(R|A)={@pra@}\\ \mathbb{P}(B) &amp;={@pb@};\quad\mathbb{P}(R|B)={@prb@}\\ \mathbb{P}(C) &amp;= {@pc@};\quad\mathbb{P}(R|C)={@prc@}.\end{aligned}\]Therefore:</p>
<ol class="HELM_parts">
<li> \[\mathbb{P}(A|R) = \frac{\mathbb{P}(R|A)\mathbb{P}(A)}{\mathbb{P}(R|A)\mathbb{P}(A)+\mathbb{P}(R|B)\mathbb{P}(B)+\mathbb{P}(R|C)\mathbb{P}(C)}={@ta1@}.\]Similarly \(\mathbb{P}(B|R)={@ta2@}\) and \(\mathbb{P}(C|R)=\displaystyle {@ta3@}.\)</li>
<li> Since each reader is independent we have \(\mathbb{P}(D) = \mathbb{P}(A|R)\times\mathbb{P}(A|R) =\displaystyle {@ta4@}.\)</li>
</ol>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
